      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">What is a crypto wallet and how does it work?</p>
          <h2  id="b-what-wallet">What Is a Crypto Wallet?</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>A cryptocurrency wallet is a tool that stores your <strong>private keys</strong> and allows you to send, receive, and manage digital assets. Despite the name, wallets don't actually store your coins or tokens &mdash; those exist as records on the blockchain. Your wallet holds the cryptographic keys that prove your ownership and authorize transfers.</p>
            <blockquote><p>A wallet is more like a keychain than a wallet. It doesn't hold money &mdash; it holds the keys that unlock your money on the blockchain.</p></blockquote>
            <p>Wallets come in many forms, each designed for different use cases:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Mobile apps</strong> &mdash; convenient, always with you, ideal for everyday transactions</li>
              <li><strong>Desktop software</strong> &mdash; more control, larger screen, suitable for managing multiple accounts</li>
              <li><strong>Browser extensions</strong> &mdash; seamless interaction with DeFi protocols and dApps</li>
              <li><a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/wallet-comparison#b-hardware"><strong>Hardware devices</strong></a> &mdash; maximum security, keys are generated and stored on a dedicated chip that never connects to the internet</li>
              <li><strong>Paper wallets</strong> &mdash; a printed private key or <a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/seed-anatomy#b-what-is">seed phrase</a> for long-term <a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/wallet-comparison#b-hot-cold">cold storage</a> (now largely deprecated in favor of hardware wallets)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Regardless of the form, every wallet performs the same core functions: key storage, address generation, transaction creation, and signature production.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">What is the difference between a public key and a private key?</p>
          <h2  id="b-keys">Public Keys vs. Private Keys</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>Every wallet is built on <strong>asymmetric cryptography</strong> &mdash; a system that uses two mathematically related but functionally different keys:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Private key</strong> &mdash; a secret 256-bit number that authorizes spending. This must never be shared with anyone. Whoever controls the private key controls the funds.</li>
              <li><strong>Public key</strong> &mdash; derived mathematically from the private key using elliptic curve multiplication. It can be freely shared and is used to verify signatures and generate addresses.</li>
            </ul>
            <blockquote><p>The private key is like a signature stamp &mdash; it proves you are the owner and authorizes actions. The public key is like your mailing address &mdash; anyone can send things to it, but only you can access the contents.</p></blockquote>
            <p>The mathematical relationship between the two keys is <strong>one-directional</strong>: you can always derive the public key from the private key, but it is computationally infeasible to derive the private key from the public key. This asymmetry is the foundation of all cryptocurrency security.</p>
            <div class="guide-flow">
              <div class="guide-flow__step">
                <div class="guide-flow__num">1</div>
                <div class="guide-flow__label">Private Key</div>
                <div class="guide-flow__desc">256-bit secret</div>
              </div>
              <div class="guide-flow__arrow">→</div>
              <div class="guide-flow__step">
                <div class="guide-flow__num">2</div>
                <div class="guide-flow__label">Public Key</div>
                <div class="guide-flow__desc">Elliptic curve</div>
              </div>
              <div class="guide-flow__arrow">→</div>
              <div class="guide-flow__step">
                <div class="guide-flow__num">3</div>
                <div class="guide-flow__label">Address</div>
                <div class="guide-flow__desc">Hash + encoding</div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="callout callout-warning">
              <span class="callout-label">Critical</span>
              If someone obtains your private key, they can immediately transfer all funds associated with that key. There is no reversal mechanism on the blockchain. Protect your private keys with the same rigor you would protect a vault key.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How are cryptocurrency addresses generated?</p>
          <h2  id="b-addresses">Addresses and Receiving Funds</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>An address is derived from your public key through a series of <strong>hashing and encoding</strong> steps. It is the string you share with others to receive funds &mdash; like a bank account number, but pseudonymous and verifiable by anyone on the network.</p>
            <h3>Address Formats in Bitcoin</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Legacy (P2PKH)</strong> &mdash; starts with <code>1</code>, the original format</li>
              <li><strong>Nested SegWit (P2SH)</strong> &mdash; starts with <code>3</code>, backward-compatible SegWit</li>
              <li><strong>Native SegWit (Bech32)</strong> &mdash; starts with <code>bc1q</code>, lower fees, better error detection</li>
              <li><strong>Taproot (Bech32m)</strong> &mdash; starts with <code>bc1p</code>, latest format with enhanced privacy and scripting capabilities</li>
            </ul>
            <p>For Ethereum and EVM chains, addresses are 40-character hex strings prefixed with <code>0x</code>, derived from the last 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the public key.</p>
            <div class="callout callout-tip">
              <span class="callout-label">Best Practice</span>
              Use a new address for each transaction to improve privacy. HD wallets handle this automatically by generating sequential addresses from the same seed. Address reuse allows blockchain observers to link your transactions together.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How does transaction signing work in crypto?</p>
          <h2  id="b-signing">Sending Funds &mdash; Transaction Signing</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>When you send cryptocurrency, your wallet performs a precise sequence of steps:</p>
            <ol>
              <li><strong>Construct the transaction</strong> &mdash; specify the recipient address, amount, and fee</li>
              <li><strong>Create a hash</strong> &mdash; the wallet computes a cryptographic hash of the transaction data</li>
              <li><strong>Sign the hash</strong> &mdash; your private key produces a digital signature over the hash</li>
              <li><strong>Broadcast</strong> &mdash; the signed transaction is sent to the network</li>
              <li><strong>Verification</strong> &mdash; network nodes verify the signature against your public key to confirm authorization</li>
            </ol>
            <p>The beauty of this system is that the private key is used to <em>create</em> the signature, but the public key is sufficient to <em>verify</em> it. Your private key never leaves the wallet during a transaction &mdash; only the signature does.</p>
            <blockquote><p>Signing a transaction is like signing a check with invisible ink that only reveals itself under a specific UV light (your public key). Anyone can verify it is genuine, but no one can forge your signature.</p></blockquote>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">What is an HD wallet and why does it use one seed for many keys?</p>
          <h2  id="b-hd-wallets">HD Wallets &mdash; One Seed, Unlimited Keys</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>Modern wallets are <strong>Hierarchical Deterministic (HD)</strong>, meaning they derive all private keys, public keys, and addresses from a single <a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/seed-anatomy#b-what-is">seed phrase</a> using a tree-like structure.</p>
            <p>This design provides powerful advantages:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Single backup</strong> &mdash; one seed phrase protects all current and future keys</li>
              <li><strong>Multi-coin support</strong> &mdash; the same seed can derive keys for Bitcoin, Ethereum, and dozens of other cryptocurrencies simultaneously</li>
              <li><strong>Automatic address generation</strong> &mdash; wallets generate fresh receiving addresses without user intervention</li>
              <li><strong>Account isolation</strong> &mdash; different derivation paths create logically separate accounts under one seed</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="callout callout-info">
              <span class="callout-label">Key Insight</span>
              An HD wallet can generate billions of unique addresses from one seed phrase. Every single one of them can be recovered by importing the same seed into any compatible wallet software. Your funds are never "in" the wallet app &mdash; they are on the blockchain, accessible with the right key.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>

